div.div:
The story follows a protagonist whose name is written with the characters for "Hoshizora" ("Starry Sky" in Japanese), but whose name is pronounced as "Nasa". On the day of his high school entrance exams, Nasa encounters a beautiful girl named Tsukasa. For Nasa, it feels like destiny is finally calling out to him that he will have a girlfriend, but things take a turn for the worse when Nasa is hit by a car and unable to attend his entrance exams.
After Tsukasa helps the injured Nasa, he confesses his feelings to her, and she agrees to go out with him, but only if Nasa agrees to marry her first. A year later Nasa aces the entrance exams, but he decides to work a part time job and live by himself instead of going to school. After Nasa turns 18, Tsukasa re-appears, and their happy, romantic, and mysterious married life together begins.
(Source: Crunchyroll)
Senpai ga Uzai Kouhai no Hanashi

Being seen as a full-fledged business woman isnt easy for Futaba Igarashi when her senpai, Harumi, treats her like a kid. Days for her are never typical, at work or outside of it, with all the antics going on in her life. As mishaps ensue, shell find herself growing closer with her loudmouth senpai. Maybe Futaba feels more than she lets on, but one things for sure: shes still annoyed!
(Source: Funimation)
Youkya na Kanojo wa Kyorikan ga Bug tte Iru: Deatte Soku wo Mochikaeri Shicha Damenano?

Komamoto Kyota is a high school boy who dotes on his 3-year-old sister. His parents both work, so he handles all the housework and childcare at home. Akiyama Sumi is a beautiful, smart, but solitary girl whose intimidating presence keeps everyone at arm's length. When Kyota went to his sister's kindergarten entrance ceremony, he found Sumi there with flushed cheeks, snapping pictures like a pro photographer. "Gosh, how adorable...... she is!" They became friends and gradually grew closer as they learned that they are both taking care of younger siblings. They cook together, help each other pick up the kids from kindergarten, and go on holiday outings. Yes, their relationship is truly that of "mommy's friend." A romantic comedy about child-raising!
(Source: Gagaga Bunko, translated)
